  <PNotes>
    <ul style="font-size: 0.7em">
      <li>
        1. Noto Fonts (Google Noto) Description: Noto is a font family developed
        by Google to cover all the languages of the world. The name "Noto" comes
        from "No Tofu", referring to the goal of eliminating the square
        characters (tofu) that appear when a font does not support a certain
        character. Examples: Noto Sans, Noto Serif, Noto Mono.
      </li>
      <li>
        2. Arial Unicode MS Description: Arial Unicode MS is an extended version
        of the popular Arial font, designed to include a wide range of Unicode
        characters. Common use: Multilingual documents, especially in corporate
        environments.
      </li>
      <li>
        3. DejaVu Fonts Description: DejaVu is an open-source font family that
        extends the Bitstream Vera font, adding support for a wide range of
        Unicode characters. Examples: DejaVu Sans, DejaVu Serif, DejaVu Sans
        Mono.
      </li>
      <li>
        4. Code2000 Description: Code2000 is a shareware font designed to
        support as many Unicode characters as possible. Common use: Linguistic
        research, technical documentation.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </PNotes>
